item.title: U.S. Watches North Korea Amid Questions About Leader's Health
item.description: The White House is closely monitoring developments regarding the status of North Korean dictator Kim Jong Un, amid speculation that the leader has undergone medical care.

item.title: 'The French Are Very Bad at Picking Asparagus.' Virus Imperils European Farming.
item.description: Covid-19 is raising questions about the viability of an economic system built on borderless migration and a single marketplace that matches labor supply with demand. Nowhere is that more apparent than in the sudden reordering of the bloc’s agricultural industry.

item.title: Britain's Ancient Parliament Goes Virtual to Cope With Coronavirus
item.description: Britain’s House of Commons, one of the world’s oldest elected assemblies, reopened its doors offering a taste of ancient democracy repurposed for the coronavirus age.

item.title: Israeli Unity Government Faces First Test: to Annex or Not to Annex
item.description: One issue looms large for Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and opposition leader Benny Gantz’s shaky political union in Israel: forging ahead on pledges to begin annexing parts of the West Bank.

item.title: Slow to Close Businesses, Italy's Economic Hub Can't Shake Off Coronavirus
item.description: Italy’s coronavirus pandemic passed its peak three weeks ago. But the ebbing of contagion is slow, prolonging the pain of the national lockdown, and the biggest problem is where it all began: Lombardy.

item.title: Singapore Had a Coveted Virus Plan. What Went Wrong?
item.description: Singapore had a plan to fight the coronavirus from the very start, with one of the world’s best contact-tracing operations. Now its infections are rising quickly.

item.title: China Bat Expert Says Wuhan Lab Wasn't Source of New Coronavirus
item.description: Virologist Shi Zhengli and her colleagues are battling suspicions that the coronavirus that causes Covid-19 escaped from her laboratories in Wuhan, where the outbreak was first identified.
